# Data Protection Standard

## Purpose

Define how personally identifiable information (PII) and sensitive data are classified, stored, processed, retained, and deleted in the enterprise e-commerce platform.

Compliance targets: GDPR, CCPA (where applicable), and general data protection best practices.

---

## Data Classification

| Class | Examples | Handling |
|-------|----------|----------|
| Public | Product catalog, category names | No restrictions |
| Internal | Order counts, aggregate analytics | Employee access only |
| Confidential | Customer email, name, address | Encrypted at rest, access logged |
| Restricted | Password hashes, payment tokens | Strong encryption, minimal access |
| Prohibited | PAN, CVV | Never stored — Stripe only |

Label new data fields with classification during schema design.

---

## PII Inventory

| Data | Table/Location | Purpose | Retention |
|------|----------------|---------|-----------|
| Email | customers.email | Account, order comms | Account lifetime + 7 years |
| Name | customers, addresses | Shipping, billing | Same |
| Phone | addresses.phone | Delivery contact | Same |
| Physical address | addresses, order snapshots | Fulfillment | Same |
| IP address | audit_log | Fraud, security | 90 days |
| Password hash | customers.password_hash | Authentication | Account lifetime |
| Order history | orders, order_lines | Fulfillment, support | 7 years (tax/legal) |
| Payment metadata | payment_records | Reconciliation | 7 years |

Review inventory annually and on new feature development.

